{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b84b0e3f-61c2-4bc4-95bd-23b5e7335dca","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. These contain the stack trace, register state, and loaded images.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the same reports.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores typically land in /cores/\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Note: SIP (System Integrity Protection) may prevent core dump generation. You can inspect a core with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.XXXX ./YourApp\n   ```\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, the `.ips` crash report is usually your best bet since `createdump` isn't bundled. The report includes the faulting thread's stack, which you can symbolicate if you have debug symbols.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"73abff36-b55c-4361-bf4e-3e06acacc6b6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":345,"requestId":"2C5C:26FA86:16A667C:198578A:69F94C43"},"id":"a5bd6dfc-825d-4160-942a-2dbae254edfa","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:47:57.492Z","parentId":"bfa4d5d4-03fd-4b23-808b-aa7530dd5dfb"}
